  status="Available"
  license="Commercial license"
>

<h2>What it does</h2>

<p>
  Krabby is a production-grade web crawler that extracts structured content from any website &mdash; whether it serves plain HTML, renders everything client-side with JavaScript, or hides content behind login walls and multi-step forms. Similar in scope to Firecrawl and Spider, but built from scratch for performance and flexibility.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>Three crawling modes</h2>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Mode 1</div>
  <h4>Static crawling</h4>
  <p>
    High-throughput HTTP-based crawling for server-rendered pages. Parses HTML directly without a browser, handling rate limiting, retries, and redirect chains. Ideal for documentation sites, blogs, wikis, and any content served as plain HTML.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Mode 2</div>
  <h4>Dynamic crawling</h4>
  <p>
    For JavaScript-heavy sites &mdash; SPAs, dashboards, client-rendered apps &mdash; the crawler spins up headless browser instances to fully render pages before extraction. Waits for async content, handles infinite scroll, and captures content injected by client-side frameworks.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Mode 3</div>
  <h4>Agentic crawling</h4>
  <p>
    An AI-driven workflow that navigates complex access patterns: logging into authenticated portals, filling out multi-step forms, accepting cookie consent banners, and following conditional navigation flows. The agent observes page state, decides what actions to take, and adapts when the expected flow changes &mdash; reaching content that no traditional crawler can.
  </p>
</div>

<hr />

<h2>Key capabilities</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Structured extraction:</strong> Configurable extraction rules that output clean JSON. Define schemas for the data you need and the crawler maps page content to your structure.</li>
  <li><strong>Deduplication:</strong> Content-aware deduplication so you don't store the same content served from different URL patterns.</li>
  <li><strong>Politeness controls:</strong> Per-domain rate limiting, configurable delays, and user-agent rotation. Crawl at scale without getting blocked.</li>
  <li><strong>Incremental crawling:</strong> Tracks what has changed since the last crawl. Re-crawl a large site and only process the pages that actually changed.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2>Built for</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Search and retrieval systems that need fresh, structured web content</li>
  <li>RAG pipelines that require high-quality source documents from across the web</li>
  <li>Competitive intelligence and market monitoring</li>
  <li>Research data collection from institutional and gated sources</li>
  <li>Content migration and archival projects</li>
</ul>

